7. Lege Plautia] A law de vi, i. e. against public violence, carried by M. Plautius sylvanus, a tribune of the plebs, An. 665. It made the offence of wearing arms in the city, and occupying the public places with an armed force, capital, in the Roman sense, i. e. involving loss of caput, or civil condition, whether by death, or, as an alternative, by sels-banishment.

8. L. Paullo] This was L. Aemilius Lepidus Paullus, brother of the triumvir M. Lepidus, consul A. U. 704. He was proscribed by the triumvirs A. U. 711, but escaped death.

9. Et ut sui] The MSS. fluctuate between this and the much easier readings, aut sui ; ac sui ; vel sui ; quasi sui. In
